AU  - Brett, Craig
AU  - Weymark, John A.
Y1  - 2008/02/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00479.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 255
EP  - 290
VL  - 49
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00479.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Comparative static properties of the solution to an optimal nonlinear income tax problem are provided for a model in which the government both designs an income tax schedule for redistributive purposes and provides a public good optimally. There are two types of individuals, distinguished by their skill levels, who have the same quasilinear preferences for labor supply and the consumption of a private and a public good. Comparative statics are obtained for the weights in a weighted utilitarian social welfare function, the prices of the two goods, a taste parameter that measures the onerousness of working, and the skill levels.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - OPTIMAL FISCAL POLICY IN THE DESIGN OF SOCIAL SECURITY REFORMS*
AU  - Conesa, Juan C.
AU  - Garriga, Carlos
Y1  - 2008/02/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00480.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 291
EP  - 318
VL  - 49
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00480.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The quantitative literature has documented that a privatization of the social security system generates large long-run welfare gains at the cost of welfare losses for transition generations. In this article, we maximize over the entire policy space, following the optimal fiscal policy approach. The resulting allocation, by construction, lies on the constrained Pareto frontier. We find that the optimal design of reforms exhibits sizeable welfare gains arising from a reduction in labor supply distortions. In contrast, the welfare gains coming from the reduction of savings distortions are relatively small.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - ATTRACTING SKEPTICAL BUYERS: NEGOTIATING FOR INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RIGHTS*
AU  - Anton, James J.
AU  - Yao, Dennis A.
Y1  - 2008/02/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00481.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 319
EP  - 348
VL  - 49
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00481.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Expropriable disclosures of knowledge to prospective buyers may be necessary to facilitate the sale of intellectual property (IP). In principle, confidentiality agreements can protect disclosures by granting the seller rights to sue for unauthorized use. In practice, sellers often waive confidentiality rights. We provide an incomplete information explanation for the waiver of confidentiality rights that are valuable in complete information settings. Waiving sacrifices the protective value of confidentiality to gain greater buyer participation. Buyer skepticism, which reduces participation, arises endogenously from three elements: asymmetric information regarding seller IP, rent dissipation from competition for IP, and ex post costs from expropriation lawsuits.
ER  - 

